Thanks natso26 and J_Koizumi_144 for further optimizing the $\inf$ lower bound! We obtain a small additional improvement using this last shifting construction by J_Koizumi_144. For $a \in [-1.7877, -\sqrt{2}]$, define the measure $$
u_a = \delta_a + 1.27383\,\delta_{a+1.7877} + 0.34979\,\delta_{a+2.73436}.$$ Then $U_{
u_a} > 0$ on $[-1, 1]$, as can be verified here. This implies that $\inf \geq 1.7877$. Two remarks about this construction. First, it is interesting that $U_{
u_a}$ is positive on the entire interval $[-1,1]$, rather than only on $\{-1\} \cup [0,1]$. So perhaps it is indeed not helpful to focus on this smaller region in some situations. Second, despite some effort, I could not make the construction work with $-1.7878$ in place of $-1.7877$ and believe this is close to the limit for this particular approach (with three atoms). Finally, this approach in general involves a family of measures $$ 
u_b = \sum_i p_i(b) \, \delta_{r_i(b)} $$ for $b$ in some interval, satisfying $U_{
u_b} > 0$ on $\{-1\} \cup [0,1]$, where the atoms move in a diagonal direction, that is, $r_i(b) = s_i \pm b$ for every $i$. It turns out that it is also helpful to fix the location of some of the atoms, as this can provide more information about the minimizing measure $\mu$. An example of this is the proof that we may assume $(-1.53,0] \subseteq \{U_\mu>0\}$, which uses a family of measures composed of two atoms $
u_{a,b} = \delta_a + B(a)\delta_b$, where $b \in [b_{\min}(a), b_{\max}(a)]$ and $a$ is fixed. I believe that the same sort of family of measures, but with three atoms, may allow us to show that $(-1.708,0] \subseteq \{U_\mu>0\}$.

Nice work, natso26! I had already given up on the three atom approach, and I am surprised that you managed to push it further. This motivated me to look at the four atom case. However, before doing so I'm going to show that we may assume $[-1.708,0] \subseteq \{U_\mu>0\}$ for a minimizing measure $\mu$. For $a \in [-1.708,-\sqrt{2}]$ and $b \in [0,1.836+a]$, consider $$ 
u_{a,b} = \delta_a + (1.395-b)\delta_b + C\,\delta_{1.071-b}, $$ where $C>0$ is chosen so that $U_{
u_{a,b}}(-1)=0.0001$. As can be seen here, we have $U_{
u_{a,b}} > 0$ on $\{-1\} \cup [0,1]$. We now claim that $[-1.708,0] \subseteq \{U_\mu>0\}$. Assume otherwise, then the infimum of $\{U_\mu>0\}$ is $a_0 \in [-1.708,0]$, with $U_\mu(a_0)=0$. Since $U_{
u_{a_0,b}}>0$ on $\{-1\}\cup[0,1]$ for every $b \in [0,1.836+a_0]$, by the duality principle, either $b$ or $1.071-b$ belongs to $\{U_\mu>0\}$. Note that both $b$ and $1.071-b$ are positive and are never equal to each other. It follows that $\{U_\mu>0\} \cap (0,+\infty)$ has measure at least $1.836+a_0$. Since we also have $(a_0,0] \subseteq \{U_\mu>0\}$, we conclude that $|\{U_\mu>0\}| \geq 1.836$, and therefore $\mu$ cannot be a minimizing measure. Now we turn to the four atom approach. We are going to show that $\inf \geq 1.8$. For $a \in [-1.8,-\sqrt{2}]$, consider $$\lambda_a=\delta_a + 1.08\,\delta_{a+1.8} + 0.2107\,\delta_{a+2.66996}+ 0.1326\,\delta_{a+2.79}.$$ As can be checked here, we have $U_{\lambda_a} > 0$ on $[-1,1]$. Therefore, for $a \in [-1.8,-1.708)$, at least one of $a$, $a+1.8$, $a+2.66996$, $a+2.79$ belongs to $\{U_\mu>0\}$. Note that for $a$ in this range these four numbers are distinct, and none of them lies in $[-1.708,0]$. It follows that $|\{U_\mu>0\} \setminus [-1.708,0]| \geq 1.8 - 1.708$. Since we already know that $[-1.708,0] \subseteq \{U_\mu>0\}$, we conclude that $\inf \geq 1.8$. Finally, I would like to mention that I did not optimize these parameters, and there is likely room for further improvement. The measures above were obtained using the program that I shared earlier, together with some experimentation in Desmos.

This proves that the $sup$ is indeed $2 \sqrt 2$! Congrats to all. Some comments: - Sign change in definition of logarithmic potential is good because it accords with literature. - Nitpick: In proof of Cor 1.1, it's not "by the fundamental theorem of algebra" because we just assumed all roots real... (Edit: this is fine. The problem statement on this site has "degree $n$ with $n$ real roots" but yours is slightly different.) - Proof of Lemma 1.2 line -4: $t_0 - 1 \leq s \leq t \leq t_0 + 1$ should be $t_0 - 1 \leq s_0 \leq t \leq t_0 + 1$ ($s$ to $s_0$). Idea of Lemma 1.2: (I use the original notation in previous comments.) Instead of trying to establish $U_{	ilde{
u}}(x) \geq U_{
u}(x)$ at the same point $x$, which doesn't work directly, we have to do $U_{	ilde{
u}}(	ilde{x}) \geq U_{
u}(x)$, where the pairing $x$ with $	ilde{x}$ is "in accord" with mass movement. Because $
u$ is the most "tight" configuration and anything else simply expands outward, that works. This is a very powerful idea. In your language, this rigorously establishes that the "toy" case is the strongest version of the problem in some specific sense. Since we don't have to worry about the complexity of rearrangement, there are likely many choices of test measures that work now, as you said.
